#Text=Wikinews interviews US National Archives Wikipedian in Residence
#Text=Thursday , June 30 , 2011
#Text=Dominic McDevitt-Parks speaks during a January 2011
#Text=Wikipedia Campus Ambassador training event .
#Text=Image : Sage Ross .
#Text=The National Archives at College Park , Maryland , known informally as Archives II , was built due to space constraints at the main building in Washington , D.C. .
#Text=Image : National Archives and Records Administration .

#Text=Dominic McDevitt-Parks , a prolific contributor to Wikipedia and a graduate student in history and archives management , agreed to answer a few questions about his new role as " Wikipedian in Residence " at the US National Archives and Records Administration .

column1: #Text=According to a Pew Internet report , 42 percent of Americans use Wikipedia as an online source of information .
#Text=The online , collaborative encyclopedia boasts more than 3.5 million articles in English and versions in over 250 languages .

#Text=Given the website 's vast readership , the Archivist of the United States has proclaimed himself " a big fan of Wikipedia " and emphasizes the need for the National Archives to work with the project .

#Text=The Archives posted the internship listing in March , expressing its desire for an employee who " will work as a community coordinator and strengthen the relationship between the Archives and the Wikipedian community through a range of activities " .

column1: #Text=McDevitt-Parks , who describes himself as a " history buff , a word nerd , a news junkie and an occasional pedant , " is a 24-year-old graduate student at Simmons College in Boston .
#Text=On Wikipedia , he has contributed for more than seven years under the username " Dominic " , his work focusing mostly on Latin American history .

#Text=He began his work at the Archives in late May , and since then he has undertaken numerous projects , including uploading onto Wikipedia 200 photos taken by Ansel Adams for the National Park Service .
#Text=Although those photos have always remained in the public domain , accessing their high-definition versions could be problematic .
#Text=Researchers who wanted to view the files had to visit the Archives facilities in College Park , Maryland .

#Text=McDevitt-Parks is also preparing a " Today 's Document challenge " on Wikipedia , where works featured as " Today 's Document " on the Archives ' website are also the main focus of newly written or expanded encyclopedia articles displayed on Wikipedia 's home page .

#Text=The first — and so far only — winner of the challenge was the Wikipedia article " Desegregation in the United States Marine Corps " , which incorporated an Archives-held photo of the first African-American recruit to the US Marine Corps .
